Embeddings live in a typed column. The column declares its dimension ahead of time: vector(768) for SBERT, 3072 for text-embedding-3-large. Similarity queries use one of three distance operators. Cosine distance is the middle dot operator written as `<=>` in SQL. Example:
ALTER TABLE docs ADD COLUMN embedding vector(768);
SELECT id, text FROM docs ORDER BY embedding <=> query_embedding LIMIT 10;
Three operators: `<=>` Cosine (default for text embeddings), `<->` L2 Euclidean (some vision embeddings), `<#>` negative inner product (normalized + fast). Cosine is default because SBERT-family embeddings are direction-carriers, not magnitude-carriers.

Without an index, ORDER BY ... <=> ... does brute-force search over every row. For production create an index: HNSW (graph, better recall, slower build) or IVFFlat (cluster probe, faster build, lower memory). HNSW params: m = 16, ef_construction = 64, ef_search = 40 - better recall + latency, slower to build. IVFFlat params: lists = sqrt(N), probes = sqrt(lists), fast to build, smaller memory, needs tuning per size. Create index SQL:
CREATE INDEX ON docs USING hnsw (embedding vector_cosine_ops) WITH (m = 16, ef_construction = 64);
SET hnsw.ef_search = 40;
Tuning is SQL. Logging, query planning, and EXPLAIN ANALYZE work the same as any other Postgres index.

The hidden payoff: vectors live next to existing rows, so you can join, filter, transact, and query metadata in SQL you already write. Other vector DBs bolt on filtering and joins; Postgres always had them. Inherited features: Transactions + ACID (insert row and vector in one atomic write), SQL joins (join docs to users to permissions to embeddings in one query), rich metadata queries (GIN indexes on JSONB, partial indexes, window functions), existing ops (backups, WAL replication, monitoring, PITR already in place). Compound query example on cat corpus:
SELECT d.id, d.text, u.name FROM docs d JOIN users u ON u.id = d.owner_id WHERE u.tenant_id = 42 ORDER BY d.embedding <=> query_embedding LIMIT 10;
One query covers similarity search, metadata filtering (tenant_id), and a join to users. Other vector DBs need multiple systems or extra services to do this.

Elastic / OpenSearch: if you already run Elastic, dense_vector is compelling. If your team already runs an Elasticsearch or OpenSearch cluster for log search and full-text queries, adding vector search is a one-field change. Both products now support a `dense_vector` field with HNSW indexes; hybrid search with BM25 is native because Elastic was always a BM25 engine. The bar to add vectors is lower than introducing a new database. Adding a dense_vector field to an existing Elastic index:

{ "mappings": { "properties": {
  "embedding": { "type": "dense_vector",
    "dims": 768,
    "index": true, "similarity": "cosine" }
} } }

Pick if: your team already runs Elastic / OpenSearch. Unified search across logs, text, and vectors. Hybrid BM25 + dense is native, not bolted on. The argument for Elastic+vector is almost entirely operational: zero new infrastructure, one query language. If vector is incidental to a larger search product, this often wins.

Or ask for structured citations. JSON output is machine-parseable and downstream audit pipelines can ingest it without regex. Schema pairs the answer with its citations and a confidence score:

{
  "answer": "Your account locks after 5 failed logins.",
  "citations": [
    { "doc_id": "doc-12", "chunk_id": 3, "quote": "5 failed login attempts" }
  ],
  "confidence": 0.92
}

Structured output makes citations machine-parseable; better for downstream audit pipelines.

Decision 4: Context Packing and Generation (Chapters 12.22, 12.23, 12.24). Choice: high token budget (16-30k tokens of retrieved context per query). Relevance-first ordering with sandwich pattern (12.22) to fight lost-in-middle (12.23). Mandatory inline citations via prompt template (12.24). I-don't-know clause if no jurisdiction-matching cases. Why: legal work needs many cases to reason across. Token budget high because cost budget is high. Sandwich (place top hits at start AND end) anchors model attention. Citation mandatory for audit. Refusal preferable to fabrication. Tradeoff: higher per-query LLM cost, accepted given $0.05 budget. Capstone Prompt Template:

System: You are a legal research assistant. Cite every case you reference using [Case Name, Year] format. Only use the provided cases. If no provided case answers, say 'I don't have case law for this question in the provided jurisdiction'.

Provided Cases:
[Case A] {summary + key holdings}
...
[Case J] {summary + key holdings}

Question: {user question}
Jurisdiction: {jurisdiction}
Answer:

Examples teach the model what to say. A JSON schema forces the response into a fixed shape - field names, allowed values, types, ranges. The model literally cannot return free-form prose if the API enforces this. Output schema:
{
  "type": "object",
  "properties": {
    "category":   { "enum": ["billing", "product", "troubleshooting"] },
    "urgency":    { "enum": ["low", "medium", "high"] },
    "confidence": { "type": "number", "minimum": 0, "maximum": 1 }
  },
  "required": ["category", "urgency", "confidence"]
}
Three locks: Enums lock the values - category must be one of three strings, no new categories invented at runtime. Required locks the fields - all three fields must appear, API rejects response if any missing. Ranges lock the numbers - confidence is a number between 0 and 1, no 1.4, no -0.2, no 'maybe'.

Schema First, Implementation Second. The schema is the contract between you and the model. Before you write one line of the real function, you write the schema. The model only ever sees the schema - never the implementation - so the schema must say everything that matters.

Tool Schema (shape):
{
  "name": "lookup_customer",
  "description": "Look up a customer by email address.",
  "input_schema": {
    "type": "object",
    "properties": {
      "email": { "type": "string", "format": "email" }
    },
    "required": ["email"]
  }
}

Four pieces:
PIECE 1 Name: "name": "lookup_customer" - the identifier the model emits when it calls this tool.
PIECE 2 Description: "description": "Look up a customer by email address." - plain-English contract. This is how the model decides WHEN to call.
PIECE 3 Input_schema: "input_schema": { "type": "object", "properties": {...} } - the JSON-Schema shape of the arguments. Type-checked before execution.
PIECE 4 Required: "required": ["email"] - which properties the model MUST provide. Others are optional.

Schema is what the model sees. Implementation is what your runtime runs. The model has never seen your real lookup_customer function. It only sees this JSON-Schema document. Everything you want it to know - the input shape, the required fields, when to call - must live inside these four pieces.

What's Required, What's Optional? JSON-Schema splits arguments into two buckets: required (must be present) and optional (may be omitted). The model reads the required list and treats it as non-negotiable. Everything else is its judgment call.

process_refund schema (excerpt):
"input_schema": {
  "type": "object",
  "properties": {
    "invoice_id": { "type": "string" },
    "reason":     { "type": "string" }
  },
  "required": ["invoice_id"]
}

REQUIRED invoice_id: { "type": "string" } - Model MUST provide. Refund cannot happen without an invoice to refund.
OPTIONAL reason: { "type": "string" } - Model decides. Empty reason is allowed - audit logs still record the refund.

Required = model MUST provide. Optional = model decides. Mark fewer fields required. Every required field is a chance for the model to give up and answer in plain text instead of calling. Make invoice_id required, but let reason be optional - the refund still works without a reason string.

Narrowing The Allowed Values. A free-form string is a footgun. The model can invent any value it likes. Use enum to lock a parameter to a fixed set of strings, and format to hint at the expected shape for things like emails, dates, and URIs.

escalate_human schema (excerpt):
"input_schema": {
  "type": "object",
  "properties": {
    "transcript": { "type": "string" },
    "urgency":    { "type": "string", "enum": ["low", "medium", "high"] }
  },
  "required": ["transcript", "urgency"]
}

urgency: { "type": "string", "enum": ["low", "medium", "high"] } - Enum locks the value. The model cannot invent urgent or critical - only the 3 allowed strings.
transcript: { "type": "string" } - Free-form string. The model writes the handoff summary in its own words.

Format Hint Example (lookup_customer): "email": { "type": "string", "format": "email" } - Format hints push the model to produce a parseable email. Your runtime can also reject malformed values before calling the function.

Enum locks the value. Format hints the shape. Both shrink the model's mistake surface. Without the enum, the model might emit urgency: "urgent" or "critical" and your ticket router would drop the request. With the enum, low / medium / high are the only legal values - the model is forced into your schema.

Our Reference Tool: lookup_customer. This is the canonical reference shape every later chapter in Section 13 builds on. The full schema below is the contract; the tool_use block underneath shows exactly what the model emits when it decides to call this tool. Bookmark this slide.

Canonical Tool Schema:
{
  "name": "lookup_customer",
  "description": "Look up a customer by email address. Returns customer_id, plan, and account status. Read-only - safe to retry.",
  "input_schema": {
    "type": "object",
    "properties": {
      "email": { "type": "string", "format": "email" }
    },
    "required": ["email"]
  }
}

Example tool_use Invocation:
{
  "type": "tool_use",
  "id": "toolu_01ABCxyz",
  "name": "lookup_customer",
  "input": { "email": "alice@example.com" }
}

Name: lookup_customer. Required Input: email (format: email). Side Effects: None. Read-only and safe to retry.

Reference shape. Every later chapter assumes this exact lookup_customer contract. Notice how every part of the previous slides shows up here: a clear name, a description that states the side-effect profile, an input_schema with a format constraint, and a required list with one element. When you see lookup_customer in later chapters, this is the schema we mean.

Tool-Use: Model Asks Runtime To Call. When the model decides to call a tool, generation halts and it emits a single tool_use block with four load-bearing fields. Canonical message:
{
  "type": "tool_use",
  "id": "toolu_01abc...",
  "name": "reset_password",
  "input": { "customer_id": "c-9924" }
}
Fields: type is always the literal string "tool_use" - tells the runtime this block is a call request. id is unique per call - the matching tool_result must carry this same id back. name is which tool to call - must match one of the schema names registered. input is the arguments - validated against the input_schema before the runtime executes. tool_use = type + id + name + input. That is the whole contract. The customer_id c-9924 inside input came from a previous tool_result in the same conversation - the model carries values forward between turns.

Discovery is what makes MCP plug-and-play. The host sends a tools/list request; the server responds with the full catalog: each tool's name, human-readable description, and JSON schema for its input. Example tools/list response:

{
  "tools": [
    {
      "name": "search_kb",
      "description": "Search the customer support knowledge base.",
      "input_schema": { "query": "string" }
    },
    {
      "name": "lookup_customer",
      "description": "Look up customer by email.",
      "input_schema": { "email": "string" }
    }
  ]
}

The host takes this list, merges it with any other servers' catalogs, and passes the combined set as the model's tool definitions on the next turn. That is how an agent built on MCP picks up new capabilities without code changes on the host.

A Prompt is a parameterized template the server publishes. The host surfaces these as slash-commands or quick actions for the user. When the user picks one, the host collects the arguments, fills the template, and sends the resulting message to the model. Example MCP Prompt shape:
{
  "name": "summarize_ticket",
  "description": "Summarize a support ticket conversation.",
  "arguments": [
    { "name": "ticket_id", "required": true },
    { "name": "max_words", "required": false }
  ]
}
The arguments array lists each parameter the template needs, with a required flag. ticket_id is required, max_words is optional. The host can either prompt the user for missing values or fill defaults before invoking.

Tool: search_kb. Registering a tool means giving it a name, a description the model will read, an input schema for arguments, and a handler that does the work server-side. Everything but the handler ships to the host; the handler stays on the server.

Server.registerTool({
  name: "search_kb",
  description: "Search the customer support knowledge base.",
  inputSchema: { query: "string" },
  handler: async ({ query }) => { /* search logic */ }
})

Name and description are what the model sees; inputSchema is the contract for the arguments. The handler is the real function and runs server-side, NOT in the model's context.

Prompt: summarize_ticket. Registering a prompt means declaring a named template and the arguments it needs. The host collects argument values from the user, then asks the server to materialize the final prompt text.

Server.registerPrompt({
  name: "summarize_ticket",
  description: "Summarize a support ticket.",
  arguments: [
    { name: "ticket_id", required: true },
    { name: "max_words", required: false }
  ],
  handler: async ({ ticket_id, max_words }) => buildPrompt(ticket_id, max_words)
})

Server returns the resolved prompt string when the host invokes it with arguments.

Before one agent can delegate to another, it has to find a peer with the right skill. A2A solves discovery with a small JSON document each agent publishes at a known URL (agent.json), containing its name, description, what skills it claims, where to reach it, and how to authenticate.

Example agent.json:
{
  "name": "billing-specialist-v2",
  "description": "Handles billing-related support tickets including refunds, downgrades, and invoice disputes.",
  "skills": ["billing", "refund", "invoice"],
  "endpoint": "https://agents.example.com/billing",
  "auth": { "type": "oauth2" }
}

Name identifies the agent. Description and skills are what other agents read to decide if this peer can help. Endpoint is the URL to call. Auth tells the caller how to prove they were granted access. Other agents discover this and decide whether to delegate.

The Customer Profile Card. Each customer has a profile card. Stable fields, queried by exact key, updated on confirmed observations. Alice's profile shape: {
  "customer_id": "c-9924",
  "tier": "Pro",
  "signed_up": "2024-08",
  "preferred_contact": "email",
  "primary_email": "alice@example.com",
  "billing_currency": "USD",
  "preferences": { "skip_onboarding_emails": true }
}. customer_id is the join key. tier, preferred_contact, billing_currency are typed fields the agent can query directly. preferences is a nested bag for arbitrarily-shaped opt-ins.

Audit logging is non-negotiable. Every tool call produces one entry with timestamp, agent identity, customer, tool name, input args, result, and consent metadata. Logs are immutable. Retention: 7 years for financial actions, per typical SOC 2 / financial-services rule. Example audit log entry shape:
{
  "timestamp":   "2026-05-16T10:34:12Z",
  "agent_id":    "billing-specialist-v2",
  "customer_id": "c-9924",
  "tool":        "process_refund",
  "input": {
    "invoice_id": "INV-9924",
    "reason":     "customer requested",
    "amount":     150
  },
  "result": {
    "status":     "success",
    "refund_id":  "rf-7821"
  },
  "consent": {
    "auto_approved": true,
    "rule":          "amount < 200"
  }
}
Logs are append-only and signed. They feed three downstream systems: incident response (recent tool calls per customer), compliance audits (retention proof), and anomaly detection (deviations from normal call patterns).

Minimum-viable agent loop in about 11 lines of Python. History list, while loop, tool dispatch when the model asks, final text when the model stops, termination on max iterations.

history = [system_prompt, user_msg]
for i in range(max_iter):
  response = llm.call(history, tools=TOOLS)
  history.append(response)
  if response.has_tool_calls():
    for tool_use in response.tool_calls:
      result = TOOLS[tool_use.name](**tool_use.input)
      history.append(tool_result_block(tool_use.id, result))
  else:
    return response.final_text
return "Max iterations reached - escalating to human."

This is the entire reason-act-observe loop. Tool dispatch lives in the TOOLS dict. Termination is either a no-tool-call response or the max_iter cap with an escalation message. Everything else (retries, observability, caching) is built on top of this skeleton.
